{{Infobox ecoregion | name = Guajira-Barranquilla xeric scrub | image = Shiyakua Wajiira.jpg | image_size = | image_alt = | image_caption = | country = [[Colombia]], [[Venezuela]] | coordinates = {{coord|11|N|74|W|display=inline,title}} | region_type = States/Provinces | bird_species = | mammal_species = | habitat_loss = | habitat_loss_ref = | protected = | protected_ref = | area = 150000 | biome = [[Deserts and xeric shrublands]] | geology = [[Cesar-Ranchería Basin|Cesar-Ranchería]], [[Cocinetas Basin|Cocinetas]], [[Guajira Basin|Guajira]], [[Maracaibo Basin|Maracaibo]], [[Sinú-San Jacinto Basin]] | conservation = }}
The '''Guajira-Barranquilla xeric scrub''' is a [[deserts and xeric shrublands|xeric shrubland]] [[ecoregion]] in [[Colombia]] and [[Venezuela]], covering an estimated area of {{convert|150000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. Rainfall varies from {{convert|125|to|1000|mm|in|abbr=on}}, and the median temperature is {{convert|26|C|F|abbr=on}}.<ref name="EoEarth">{{cite web |url=http://www.eoearth.org/view/article/153168/ |first=Mark |last=McGinley |title=Guajira-Barranquilla xeric scrub |publisher=Encyclopedia of Earth |date=2012-08-02 |accessdate=2013-10-11}}</ref>
== Location == [[File:Ranchería Wayúu.JPG|thumb|left|A [[wayuu]] rancheria. The wayuu people are the native inhabitants of the Guajira xeric scrub]] The ecoregion occupies the [[Guajira Peninsula]], the valley of [[Rancheria river]] and [[Guajira Department]], covering parts of the northeastern coast of [[Venezuela]]. The valleys lie in the [[rain shadow]] of the surrounding [[Serranía de Macuira]], which reaches an elevation of {{convert|900|m|ft|abbr=on}} over sea level. These mountains trap some of the trade winds, causing [[mist]]. An important tourist destination in the area is [[Cabo de la Vela]].
== Ecology == {{see also|Biodiversity in Colombia}} === Flora === [[File:Dividivi on aruba.jpg|thumb|Divi-divi (''[[Caesalpinia coriaria]]'')]] The ecoregion is dominated by thorny trees and [[succulent]]s. Common species include ''[[Acacia glomerosa]]'', ''[[Bourreria cumanensis]]'', ''[[Bulnesia arborea]]'', ''[[Caesalpinia coriaria]]'', ''[[Copaifera venezolana]]'', ''[[Croton (plant)|Croton]]'' sp., ''[[Gyrocarpus americanus]]'', ''[[Hyptis]]'' sp., ''[[Jacquinia pungens]]'', ''[[Malpighia glabra]]'', ''[[Myrospermum frutescens]]'', ''[[Opuntia caribaea]]'', ''[[Pereskia guamacho]]'', ''[[Piptadenia flava]]'', ''[[Prosopis juliflora]]'', and ''[[Stenocereus griseus]]''. [[File:Wajiiraka.jpg|thumb|right]] Forests dominated by ''[[Lonchocarpus punctatus]]'' are often accompanied by ''[[Bunchosia odorata]]'' and ''[[Ayenia magna]]''. Other forests exist in which ''Prosopis juliflora'', ''[[Erythrina velutina]]'' and ''[[Clerodendron ternifolium]]'' are dominant. A variety of plant communities occur where two plant species are dominant. Examples include ''[[Astronium graveolens]]'' &ndash; ''[[Handroanthus billbergii]]'', ''[[Haematoxylum brasiletto]]'' &ndash; ''[[Melochia tomentosa]]'', ''Caesalpinia coriaria'' &ndash; ''[[Cordia curassavica]]'', ''[[Bursera glabra]]'' &ndash; ''[[Castela erecta]]'', ''[[Vitex cymosa]]'' &ndash; ''[[Libidibia coraria]]'', ''[[Mimosa cabrera]]'' &ndash; ''Cordia curassavica'', ''[[Bursera tomentosa]]'' &ndash; ''[[Bursera graveolens]]'' and ''[[Castela erecta]]'' &ndash; ''[[Parkinsonia praecox]]''.<ref name="EoEarth"/>
=== Fauna === [[File:Lightmatter flamingo2.jpg|thumb|Caribbean flamingo (''Phoenicopterus ruber'')]] The ecoregion is notable for being the habitat of a large community of [[Caribbean flamingo]] (''Phoenicopterus ruber''), besides a diversity of birds and bats.
== Conservation == Most of the [[Serranía de Macuira]] lies within [[National Natural Park of Macuira]]. Nearby is the {{convert|80|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} [[Los Flamencos Sanctuary]], which is a center of plant diversity for species of ''[[Hechtia]]'', ''[[Salvia]]'', and [[cactus]]. Of the 2700 species found within, approximately 30% are [[Endemism|endemic]].
== References == {{reflist}}
== External links == * {{es icon}} Martha Ligia Castellanos, Luis Carlos Pardo L. 2000. Caracterización y primera aproximación a la determinación del índice de biodiversidad en los suelos de la cuenca del arroyo Mekijanao, Serranía de la Macuira, Alta Guajira. En: Juan Carlos Pérez (editor) X Congreso Nacional de la Ciencia del Suelo. Programa y resúmenes. El suelo un componente del medio natural. Medellín, Octubre 11 al 13 de 2000 * {{es icon}} Edith González, Gabriel Guillot, Néstor Miranda, Diana Pombo (editores). 1990. Perfil Ambiental de Colombia. Colciencias. Escala. Bogotá.
